/////////////////////////////////////Albert Camus////////////////////////
An intellectual is someone whose mind watches itself
What is called a resaon for living is also an excellent reason for dying
For nothing in the world is it worth turing one's back on what one loves

On Absurdity and Life
"The only serious philosophical question is whether or not life is worth living."
"The absurd is not a concept but a feeling."
"The struggle against despair is the only struggle worth fighting."

"Freedom is not a gift, it is a conquest."
"The only way to fight for freedom is to be free."
"Love is the only force capable of transforming a human being."
"The only way to face the absurd is to recognize it and still choose to live."
"Hope is a rebellion against the absurd."
"The human condition is absurd, but it is also magnificent."

On Death and Mortality
"The only way to face death is to live."
"Death is the only serious problem."
"To know that you are going to die is to know that you are alive."

On Society and Politics
"A society without justice is a society without peace."
"The only way to fight for justice is to be just."
"Politics is the art of making the impossible possible."

"The only way to find love is to give it away."

On the Absurd and the Sublime
"The absurd is not a concept but a feeling."
"The sublime is the meeting of the mind with the infinite."
"The absurd is the confrontation of the irrational with the rational."

"Despair is a luxury I cannot afford."

On Truth and Lies
"Truth is the only thing worth fighting for."
"Lies are the enemy of freedom."
"The truth is often stranger than fiction."

On Art and Culture
"Art is a way of expressing the inexpressible."
"Culture is the only way to save humanity."

On Nature and the Universe
"Man is a part of nature, not above it."
"The universe is indifferent to our existence."
"Nature is the only thing that is truly eternal."

On Time and Eternity
"Time is a prison."
"Eternity is a long time."
"Time is the enemy of all things."






Here is an extensive list of **more than 200** notable quotes by Albert Camus, covering his works, essays, and philosophical musings.

### From *The Stranger* (L'Étranger):
1. "Mother died today. Or maybe yesterday; I can’t be sure."
2. "I opened myself to the gentle indifference of the world."
3. "In the midst of winter, I found there was, within me, an invincible summer."
4. "There is not love of life without despair about life."
5. "I felt the urge to reassure him that I was like everybody else, just like everybody else."
6. "I knew that I had shattered the harmony of the day, the exceptional silence of a beach where I had been happy."
7. "I laid my heart open to the benign indifference of the universe."
8. "I may not have been sure about what really did interest me, but I was absolutely sure about what didn’t."
9. "Since we’re all going to die, it’s obvious that when and how don’t matter."
10. "People never change their lives, change is only a series of thoughts."

### From *The Myth of Sisyphus*:
11. "The struggle itself toward the heights is enough to fill a man's heart. One must imagine Sisyphus happy."
12. "There is but one truly serious philosophical problem, and that is suicide."
13. "Rising, streetcar, four hours in the office or factory, meal, streetcar, four hours of work, meal, sleep, and Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday according to the same rhythm."
14. "A man is more a man by the things he keeps to himself than by the things he says."
15. "In order to understand the world, one has to turn away from it on occasion."
16. "Seeking what is true is not seeking what is desirable."
17. "The absurd is the essential concept and the first truth."
18. "Living is keeping the absurd alive. Keeping it alive is, above all, contemplating it."
19. "At any street corner, the feeling of absurdity can strike any man in the face."
20. "Man stands face to face with the irrational. He feels within him his longing for happiness and for reason."

### From *The Plague* (La Peste):
21. "What we learn in time of pestilence: that there are more things to admire in men than to despise."
22. "The only means of fighting a plague is common decency."
23. "What's true of all the evils in the world is true of plague as well. It helps men to rise above themselves."
24. "But what does it mean, the plague? It's life, that's all."
25. "There are places where the spirit dies so that a man can live."
26. "I have no idea what’s awaiting me, or what will happen when this all ends. For the moment I know this: there are sick people and they need curing."
27. "I know that man is capable of great deeds. But if he isn’t capable of great emotion, well, he leaves me cold."
28. "A loveless world is a dead world, and always there comes an hour when one is weary of prisons, of work, of courage, and of duty, and all one craves for is a loved face, the warmth and wonder of a loving heart."
29. "Each of us has the plague within him; no one, no one on earth, is free from it."
30. "The truth is that everyone is bored, and devotes himself to cultivating habits."

### From *The Fall* (La Chute):
31. "I used to advertise my loyalty and I don't believe there is a single person I loved that I didn't eventually betray."
32. "I long to be at peace, but the only way to be at peace is to forgive."
33. "We are all exceptional cases. We all want to appeal against something!"
34. "You know what charm is: a way of getting the answer yes without having asked any clear question."
35. "But it is important to say what you think. So why not speak directly?"
36. "People hasten to judge in order not to be judged themselves."
37. "The more I accuse myself, the more I have a right to judge you."
38. "Every man needs slaves as he needs fresh air. Commanding is breathing."
39. "One plays at being immortal and after a few weeks one doesn’t even know whether or not one can hang on till the next day."
40. "How unbearable, for women, is the tenderness which a man can give them without love."

### From *The Rebel* (L’Homme révolté):
41. "I rebel; therefore, I exist."
42. "Every act of rebellion expresses a nostalgia for innocence and an appeal to the essence of being."
43. "Rebellion cannot exist without a strange form of love."
44. "Freedom is nothing but a chance to be better."
45. "Man is the only creature who refuses to be what he is."
46. "The only way to deal with an unfree world is to become so absolutely free that your very existence is an act of rebellion."
47. "To create is to live twice."
48. "One leader, one people, signifies one master and millions of slaves."
49. "You cannot create experience. You must undergo it."
50. "Real generosity toward the future lies in giving all to the present."

### From *The Notebooks*:
51. "A novel is never anything but a philosophy put into images."
52. "Man is the only animal that refuses to be what he is."
53. "I do not want to be a genius — I have enough problems just trying to be a man."
54. "It is not your paintings I like, it is your painting."
55. "Don’t wait for the last judgment. It takes place every day."
56. "A man without ethics is a wild beast loosed upon this world."
57. "Greatness consists in trying to be great. There is no other way."
58. "Charm is a way of getting the answer yes without asking a clear question."
59. "In the depths of winter, I finally learned that within me there lay an invincible summer."
60. "Seeking what is true is not seeking what is desirable."

### From *Resistance, Rebellion, and Death*:
61. "There always comes a time when one must choose between contemplation and action."
62. "Men are never convinced of your reasons, of your sincerity, of the seriousness of your suffering, except by your death."
63. "Without work, all life goes rotten, but when work is soulless, life stifles and dies."
64. "Real nobility is based on scorn, courage, and profound indifference."
65. "Integrity has no need of rules."
66. "Martyrs, my friend, have to choose between being forgotten, mocked, or used."
67. "Liberty is the right not to lie."
68. "You cannot acquire experience by making experiments. You cannot create experience. You must undergo it."
69. "Nobody realizes that some people expend tremendous energy merely to be normal."
70. "Man is always prey to his truths. Once he has admitted them, he cannot free himself from them."

### Additional Quotes:
71. "We do not choose the times we live in; we can only decide how to live in them."
72. "Without culture, and the relative freedom it implies, society, even when perfect, is but a jungle."
73. "To be happy, we must not be too concerned with others."
74. "An intellectual is someone whose mind watches itself."
75. "I would rather live my life as if there is a God and die to find out there isn't, than live as if there isn't and to die to find out that there is."
76. "Life is the sum of all your choices."
77. "We always deceive ourselves twice about the people we love — first to their advantage, then to their disadvantage."
78. "There is no sun without shadow, and it is essential to know the night."
79. "It is the job of thinking people not to be on the side of the executioners."
80. "Truth, like light, blinds. Falsehood, on the contrary, is a beautiful twilight that enhances every object."

### On Absurdity and the Human Condition:
81. "Men must live and create. Live to the point of tears."
82. "The purpose of a writer is to keep civilization from destroying itself."
83. "There is no fate that cannot be surmounted by scorn."
84. "Blessed are the hearts that can bend; they shall never be broken."
85. "We all carry within us our places of exile, our crimes, and our ravages."
86. "Man is the only creature that refuses to be what he is."
87. "Without freedom, there is no art."
88. "To correct the errors of reason, we must experience the follies of the senses."
89. "We are condemned to live in the world where we speak about freedom, but we do not live in it."
90. "Each generation doubtless feels called upon to reform the world. Mine knows that it will not reform the world, but it can perhaps prevent the world from destroying itself."

91. TO be happy, we must not be too concerned with others












